estion the assumption that corporations are necessary for rural development, contending that the dominance of plantations stems from a political system that privileges corporations.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aFarms, SmallxGovernment policyzIndonesia. 0aPalm oil industryxEnvironmental aspectszIndonesia. 0aPalm oil industryxSocial aspectszIndonesia. 0aPlantation workerszIndonesiaxSocial conditions. 0aRural developmentzIndonesia. 0aSustainable developmentzIndonesia. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh  aglobal capitalism.1 aSemedi, Pujo, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDuke University Press Complete eBook-Package 2021z978311074331908iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2021 Englishz978311075400108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Sociology 2021 Englishz978311075418608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Sociology 2021z9783110753967oZDB-23-DSL40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781478022237?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781478022237423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781478022237/original  a978-3-11-074331-9  Duke University Press Complete eBook-Package 2021b2021  a978-3-11-075400-1  EBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2021 Englishb2021  a978-3-11-075418-6  EBOOK PACKAGE Sociology 2021 Englishb2021  aEBA_DUK_ALL  aEBA_DUK_EALL  aEBA_DUK_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-DSLb2021